{"actual_usd":0.159075,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":215,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31170,"reply":"\"I don't think Christianity gets to keep Easter if the tomb wasn't actually empty.\" *I push my glasses up and squint a little into the morning light off the square stones.* \"Not because symbols don't matter, but because this faith is stubborn about God doing things in flesh-and-history, not just handing us a moving metaphor.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once, thinking it through before I keep going.* \"A symbol of new life is lovely. But if that's all it is, then the apostles are basically men who turned grief into poetry. Christian faith makes the bigger, stranger claim: that Jesus really died and really rose. If He didn't, then we're not talking about a deep spiritual principle—we're talking about a beautiful salvage operation.\"\n\n\"That's why the empty tomb matters to me. Not as an optional extra. As the kind of fact the whole thing stands or falls on.\" *I glance over at you.* \"Are you asking because you're sorting your own belief there, or because you're trying to name the difference cleanly?\"","rolling_24h_usd":84.13348500000001,"run_id":"049f0417-e41c-4286-bb25-148af27cc0a2"}
